items.synopsis: The Giants have the momentum at the MCG, but the Saints are still within range in their elimination final at the MCG. Whose season will end today? Follow the action in our live blog.

title.children: King inspires Saints after Giants' Orange Tsunami builds big elimination final lead

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: There is life in these Saints! It was a 42-point game not too long ago, but St Kilda have found four of the last five goals to drag themselves back into it. The Giants were mighty impressive throughout most of that quarter, but the door has been left ajar. St Kilda clearly aren't going to win this on the strength of their defence — GWS are cutting through them with ease. But when the Saints start winning some of their own ball and start moving it with confidence, it's a different game. They're coming from a long way back, but you can't count out the Saints.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Half-time: Giants lead it by 23 points

children.content: (Getty Images)
There is life in these Saints!
It was a 42-point game not too long ago, but St Kilda have found four of the last five goals to drag themselves back into it.

The Giants were mighty impressive throughout most of that quarter, but the door has been left ajar. St Kilda clearly aren't going to win this on the strength of their defence — GWS are cutting through them with ease.
But when the Saints start winning some of their own ball and start moving it with confidence, it's a different game.
They're coming from a long way back, but you can't count out the Saints.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The Saints looked as if they were settling into things nicely in the early stages of that quarter, but GWS soon found themselves in a groove and cashed in on the scoreboard. St Kilda are controlling things in the air, but at ground level the Giants are taking them apart with their run and handball game. The Saints defence is vulnerable when the ball is coming in as quickly as it was at times in that term. Still early days, but the Giants will be chuffed with what they've seen so far.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Quarter-time: Giants get the jump and lead by 18 points

children.content: (Getty Images)

St Kilda are controlling things in the air, but at ground level the Giants are taking them apart with their run and handball game. The Saints defence is vulnerable when the ball is coming in as quickly as it was at times in that term.
Still early days, but the Giants will be chuffed with what they've seen so far.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Big news out of both camps ahead of this one. Tim Membrey is out for St Kilda, replaced in the forward line by Anthony Caminiti, while we've just found out that Stephen Coniglio has been pulled from the GWS line up, replaced by Xavier O'Halloran. That Coniglio news is huge. Full final teams are below: Subs are Liam Stocker for the Saints and Nick Haynes for the Giants.

image.altText: Nathan Cleary of the Panthers runs the ball during the NRL Qualifying Final match between Penrith Panthers and New Zealand Warriors at BlueBet Stadium on September 09, 2023 in Penrith, Australia.

items.synopsis: Penrith have wasted no time getting to work in their NRL finals clash with the Warriors with Nathan Cleary setting up two early tries. Follow live.

title.children: Penrith's Nathan Cleary dominating in NRL finals battle with New Zealand

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Cleary and Luke Garner put Penrith on the front foot, with a slick left-side shift summed up by a brilliant touch pass from Stephen Crichton to winger Sunia Turuva, who accelerates into the corner for Penrith's third try of the day. And Cleary remains perfect with the boot to make it 18-0.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: The Panthers are in again!

children.content: Cleary and Luke Garner put Penrith on the front foot, with a slick left-side shift summed up by a brilliant touch pass from Stephen Crichton to winger Sunia Turuva, who accelerates into the corner for Penrith's third try of the day.
And Cleary remains perfect with the boot to make it 18-0.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Penrith halfback Nathan Cleary was brought down in a charge on the fourth tackle, but he got up so rapidly he lost a boot, got back into shape and sent back rower Liam Martin through a hole with a short ball on the next play. He converts, with both boots on now, to make it 12-0 to the Panthers after 22 minutes.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: One-shoed Nathan Cleary sets up Penrith's second

children.content: Penrith halfback Nathan Cleary was brought down in a charge on the fourth tackle, but he got up so rapidly he lost a boot, got back into shape and sent back rower Liam Martin through a hole with a short ball on the next play.

props.alt: Liam Martin celebrates a try with the Panthers.

children.content: (Getty)
He converts, with both boots on now, to make it 12-0 to the Panthers after 22 minutes.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: There was nothing on when Nathan Cleary shrugged off Mitch Barnett, but he crabbed across the field, split Dylan Walker and Jackson Ford, and flicked to Moses Leota. The big prop then pulled off a lovely cut-out pass to winger Brian To'o, who stumbled and fell to the line. Looked to me like he might have grounded the ball short, but the bunker confirms the try. Panthers lead 6-0 after six minutes.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: The Panthers score out of nowhere!

children.content: There was nothing on when Nathan Cleary shrugged off Mitch Barnett, but he crabbed across the field, split Dylan Walker and Jackson Ford, and flicked to Moses Leota.
